05027nam a22008775i 9780823262809DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232628097 a10.1515/97808232628092doi  a(DE-B1597)555110  a(OCoLC)1024259001  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aD804.5.H35 7aHIS0370702bisacsh04a940.53/182231 aKnittel, Susanne C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Historical Uncanny :bDisability, Ethnicity, and the Politics of Holocaust Memory /cSusanne C. Knittel. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (364 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Remembering Euthanasia: Grafeneck as Heterotopia -- t2. Bridging the Silence, Part I: The Disabled Enabler -- t3. Bridging the Silence, Part II: The Vicarious Witness -- t4. Lethal Trajectories: Perpetrators from Grafeneck to the Risiera -- t5. Black Holes and Revelations: The Risiera, the Foibe, and the Making of an "Italian Tragedy" -- t6. A Severed Branch: The Memory of Fascism on Stage and Screen -- t7. Bridging the Silence, Part III: Trieste and the Language of Belonging -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Historical Uncanny explores how certain memories become inscribed into the heritage of a country or region while others are suppressed or forgotten. In response to the erasure of historical memories that discomfit a public's self-understanding, this book proposes the historical uncanny as that which resists reification precisely because it cannot be assimilated to dominant discourses of commemoration.Focusing on the problems of representation and reception, the book explores memorials for two marginalized aspects of Holocaust: the Nazi euthanasia program directed against the mentally ill and disabled and the Fascist persecution of Slovenes, Croats, and Jews in and around Trieste. Reading these memorials together with literary and artistic texts, Knittel redefines "sites of memory" as assemblages of cultural artifacts and discourses that accumulate over time; they emerge as a physical and a cultural space that is continually redefined, rewritten, and re-presented.In bringing perspectives from disability studies and postcolonialism to the question of memory, Knittel unsettles our understanding of the Holocaust and its place in the culture of contemporary Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCollective memoryxPolitical aspects. 0aCroatsxCrimes againstxHistoryy20th century. 0aEuthanasiaxGovernment policyzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aHolocaust memorialsxPolitical aspectszGermany. 0aHolocaust memorialsxPolitical aspectszItaly. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xHistoriography. 0aKilling of the mentally illzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxNazi persecution. 0aSlovenesxCrimes againstxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocities. 4aCultural Memory. 4aDisability. 4aEugenics. 4aFascism. 4aGrafeneck. 4aHolocaust. 4aMemorials. 4aNazi Euthanasia. 4aPerpetrators. 4aTrieste. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823262809zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823262809423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823262809.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  